## 2. Tasks — The Foundation

A task in FreeRTOS is like a program running on your PC. Each task has its own:

- Stack (private memory for local variables)
- Priority (determines who runs when)
- State (running, ready, blocked, suspended)

### Creating a Task

```c
void my_task(void *arg)
{
    while (1) {
        ESP_LOGI("task", "I am running");
        vTaskDelay(pdMS_TO_TICKS(1000));
    }
    /* Tasks should never return.
     * If they do — call vTaskDelete(NULL) */
}

void app_main(void)
{
    xTaskCreate(
        my_task,        /* Function to run as task */
        "my_task",      /* Name — for debugging only */
        2048,           /* Stack size in bytes */
        NULL,           /* Parameter passed to task */
        5,              /* Priority — higher = more important */
        NULL            /* Handle — NULL if not needed */
    );
}
```

### Task Parameters Explained

|Parameter|What it means|Typical value|
|---|---|---|
|Function|The function that IS the task|your function|
|Name|String label for debugger|"sensor_task"|
|Stack size|Private RAM in bytes|2048 to 8192|
|Parameter|Pointer passed to function|NULL or &config|
|Priority|0 = lowest, 25 = highest|5 for most tasks|
|Handle|Pointer to control task later|NULL if not needed|

### Priority Rules

```
Priority 25  ← Highest — runs before everything
Priority 10  ← High
Priority  5  ← Medium — most application tasks
Priority  1  ← Low
Priority  0  ← Idle task — only runs when nothing else needs CPU
```

```
ESP32 Reserved Priorities (do not use these):
Priority 24  <- WiFi task
Priority 22  <- Bluetooth task
Priority 23  <- System event task

Your tasks should stay below 20.
```

## Task States

### The Setup

Imagine a team of employees (tasks) working in an office. There is only ONE computer (CPU) in the office that everyone shares.

---
### RUNNING — "At the Computer"

```
Only ONE employee can sit at the computer at a time.
This is the task currently using the CPU.
Everyone else is waiting for their turn.
```

---
### READY — "Standing in Queue at the Computer"

```
The employee has everything they need to work.
Their document is ready. Their hands are ready.
They are just waiting for the person at the
computer to finish and give them their turn.

Multiple employees can be READY at the same time.
The most senior person (highest priority) gets
to go next.
```

---
### BLOCKED — "Waiting for Something Before They Can Work"

```
Two types of waiting:

Type 1 — Waiting for time:
"I sent an email. Now I wait 30 minutes
for a reply before I do anything."
-> vTaskDelay() — task is sleeping

Type 2 — Waiting for a resource:
"I need the printer but someone else is using it.
I cannot work until it is free."
-> xQueueReceive() or xSemaphoreTake()
   task is waiting for data or a resource
```

> Blocked employees are NOT in the queue for the computer. They are sitting at their desk doing nothing. CPU is free for other employees while they wait.

---
### SUSPENDED — "Called in Sick — Completely Offline"

```
Manager explicitly told them to stop working.
They will not come back until the manager
personally calls them back.

In code:
vTaskSuspend(handle)  -> send home
vTaskResume(handle)   -> call back
```

