## 3. The FreeRTOS Scheduler

The scheduler is the brain of FreeRTOS. It decides which task runs at any given moment.

### How the Scheduler Works

```
Scheduler runs every 1ms (configTICK_RATE_HZ = 1000)

Every tick:
1. Look at all READY tasks
2. Find the highest priority READY task
3. Give it the CPU
4. If multiple tasks have the same priority — round robin

Timeline with 3 tasks:

Priority 10: sensor_task  ████░░░░████░░░░████░░░░
Priority  5: mqtt_task    ░░░░████░░░░████░░░░████
Priority  1: log_task     ░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░░

░ = blocked (sleeping or waiting)
█ = running

sensor_task runs, sleeps, mqtt_task runs, etc.
log_task only runs when BOTH others are sleeping.
```

### What Happens When Two Tasks Have Same Priority

```c
/* Task A — priority 5 */
void task_a(void *arg) {
    while (1) {
        ESP_LOGI("A", "Task A running");
        vTaskDelay(pdMS_TO_TICKS(500));
    }
}

/* Task B — priority 5 */
void task_b(void *arg) {
    while (1) {
        ESP_LOGI("B", "Task B running");
        vTaskDelay(pdMS_TO_TICKS(500));
    }
}
```

```
Output (alternates fairly):
A: Task A running
B: Task B running
A: Task A running
B: Task B running
```

FreeRTOS round-robins between equal priority tasks. Each gets one tick (1ms) before switching.

### Priority Inversion Danger

#### FreeRTOS Priority Inversion — The Intern Blocking the CEO

---
#### The Characters

```
CEO      = HIGH priority task   (priority 10)
Manager  = MEDIUM priority task (priority  5)
Intern   = LOW priority task    (priority  1)

The Meeting Room = Shared resource (mutex)
```

---

#### Normal Day — No Problem

```
CEO needs the meeting room.
Meeting room is free.
CEO walks in, does his work, walks out.
Everyone is happy.
```

---

#### The Problem Day — Priority Inversion

```
Step 1:
Intern books the meeting room (takes the mutex).
Intern is doing some low priority paperwork inside.

Step 2:
CEO urgently needs the meeting room (tries to take mutex).
Meeting room is occupied by the Intern.
CEO CANNOT enter. CEO WAITS outside.

Step 3:
Manager walks by. Manager has no interest in
the meeting room. Manager just keeps doing his work.
Manager is priority 5 — higher than Intern priority 1.
So Manager keeps running — Intern cannot finish.

Step 4:
Intern is stuck — cannot finish because Manager
keeps getting CPU time instead.
CEO is stuck — waiting for Intern to finish.
Manager is running freely — does not even need the room.

Result:
CEO (priority 10) is effectively blocked by
Manager (priority 5) — even though Manager does
not hold the resource CEO needs.

CEO is running at the LOWEST priority in the system.
This is Priority Inversion.
```

