## Why This Is Dangerous in Real Products

```
CEO    = WiFi reconnection task  (must run within 5 seconds)
Manager = Data logging task      (not urgent at all)
Intern  = Sensor reading task    (holds I2C mutex)

WiFi reconnection task waits for I2C mutex.
Intern sensor task cannot finish because logger keeps running.
WiFi reconnection times out.
Device disconnects from network.
Customer support gets a call.
```

---

## Real World Example — Mars Pathfinder 1997

This is exactly what happened on NASA's Mars Pathfinder mission.

https://kwahome.medium.com/the-first-bug-on-mars-os-scheduling-priority-inversion-and-the-mars-pathfinder-53586a631525

```
The spacecraft kept resetting itself on Mars.
Engineers could not understand why.

Root cause:
A low priority meteorological task held a shared mutex.
A high priority information bus task needed the same mutex.
A medium priority communications task kept running.

The high priority task was effectively blocked by
the medium priority task.

System watchdog detected the high priority task was
not running and reset the entire spacecraft.

Fix: Enable priority inheritance on the mutex.
     One config change. Problem solved.
     Deployed as a software patch to Mars.
```

> This bug became the most famous priority inversion in software engineering history.

---

## The Fix — Priority Inheritance

FreeRTOS mutexes fix this automatically with Priority Inheritance.

```
When CEO is waiting outside the meeting room:

FreeRTOS sees:
"CEO (priority 10) is waiting for Intern (priority 1)
 to release the mutex."

FreeRTOS temporarily promotes Intern to priority 10.

Now:
Intern runs at priority 10 — same as CEO.
Manager (priority 5) cannot interrupt Intern anymore.
Intern finishes paperwork quickly.
Intern leaves the room — drops back to priority 1.
CEO enters the room immediately.
Everything returns to normal.
```

---

## Mutex vs Binary Semaphore — The Key Difference

|Feature|Mutex|Binary Semaphore|
|---|---|---|
|Priority inheritance|YES — automatic|NO|
|Use for shared resources|YES|NO|
|Use for signalling events|NO|YES|
|One line to remember|Protects resources|Signals events|

```c
/* Protects shared resource — use mutex */
SemaphoreHandle_t i2c_mutex = xSemaphoreCreateMutex();

/* Signals an event — use binary semaphore */
SemaphoreHandle_t data_ready = xSemaphoreCreateBinary();
```

> Always use `xSemaphoreCreateMutex()` when protecting a shared peripheral or data structure. Binary semaphore does NOT have priority inheritance and will cause priority inversion.

