## 4. Queues — Safe Data Transfer Between Tasks

A queue is the correct way to pass data from one task to another.

### Why Not Use a Global Variable?

```c
/* WRONG — global variable between tasks */
float global_temperature = 0.0f;

void sensor_task(void *arg) {
    while (1) {
        global_temperature = read_dht22();  /* Write */
        vTaskDelay(pdMS_TO_TICKS(2000));
    }
}

void display_task(void *arg) {
    while (1) {
        show_on_oled(global_temperature);   /* Read */
        vTaskDelay(pdMS_TO_TICKS(1000));
    }
}
```

This looks fine but has a critical bug called a **race condition**:

```
Timeline — what can go wrong:

sensor_task writes first byte of float (0x41)
SCHEDULER SWITCHES to display_task
display_task reads half-written float: 0x41 + garbage
display_task shows wrong temperature on OLED
SCHEDULER SWITCHES back
sensor_task writes second byte (0xD9)

Result: display shows corrupted data.
In production: your product shows 350°C to a customer.
```

### Queues Solve This

A queue is a thread-safe FIFO buffer. Only one task can read or write at a time — atomically.

```
PC Analogy:

Queue = Email inbox

sensor_task SENDS an email with temperature data
display_task READS from inbox when ready

Only one person reads or writes the inbox at a time.
Data is complete before the reader sees it.
No corruption possible.
```

### Creating and Using a Queue

```c
#include "freertos/queue.h"

/* Define the data structure to pass */
typedef struct {
    float temperature;
    float humidity;
} sensor_data_t;

/* Create queue — holds 10 items of type sensor_data_t */
static QueueHandle_t sensor_queue;

void app_main(void)
{
    sensor_queue = xQueueCreate(10, sizeof(sensor_data_t));

    if (sensor_queue == NULL) {
        ESP_LOGE(TAG, "Queue creation failed — out of memory");
        return;
    }

    xTaskCreate(sensor_task, "sensor", 4096, NULL, 5, NULL);
    xTaskCreate(display_task, "display", 4096, NULL, 5, NULL);
}
```

```c
/* Producer — sends data to queue */
void sensor_task(void *arg)
{
    sensor_data_t data;

    while (1) {
        data.temperature = read_temperature();
        data.humidity    = read_humidity();

        /* Send to queue — timeout 0 means don't wait if full */
        if (xQueueSend(sensor_queue, &data, 0) != pdTRUE) {
            ESP_LOGW(TAG, "Queue full — dropped reading");
        }

        vTaskDelay(pdMS_TO_TICKS(2000));
    }
}
```

```c
/* Consumer — receives data from queue */
void display_task(void *arg)
{
    sensor_data_t data;

    while (1) {
        /* Wait forever until data arrives */
        if (xQueueReceive(sensor_queue, &data, portMAX_DELAY)) {
            show_on_oled(data.temperature, data.humidity);
            ESP_LOGI(TAG, "Temp: %.1f  Humi: %.1f",
                     data.temperature, data.humidity);
        }
    }
}
```

### Queue API Reference

|Function|When to use|
|---|---|
|`xQueueCreate(len, size)`|Create — do this in app_main|
|`xQueueSend(q, &item, 0)`|Send — don't wait if full|
|`xQueueSend(q, &item, portMAX_DELAY)`|Send — wait forever if full|
|`xQueueReceive(q, &item, portMAX_DELAY)`|Receive — block until data|
|`xQueueReceive(q, &item, 0)`|Receive — return immediately if empty|
|`xQueueSendFromISR(q, &item, NULL)`|Send from interrupt handler|
|`uxQueueMessagesWaiting(q)`|How many items in queue right now|
|`xQueueReset(q)`|Empty the queue|

