## 5. Semaphores — Protecting Shared Resources

A semaphore is a signalling mechanism between tasks. A mutex is a semaphore with ownership — the task that takes it must be the task that gives it.

### Binary Semaphore — Signalling

Use when one task needs to SIGNAL another task that something happened.

```c
/* PC Analogy:
   Binary semaphore = a doorbell
   Task A presses doorbell (give)
   Task B waiting at door hears it (take)
   Task B does the work */

static SemaphoreHandle_t data_ready_sem;

void sensor_task(void *arg) {
    while (1) {
        read_sensor();
        xSemaphoreGive(data_ready_sem);  /* Ring the doorbell */
        vTaskDelay(pdMS_TO_TICKS(2000));
    }
}

void process_task(void *arg) {
    while (1) {
        /* Wait at the door indefinitely */
        xSemaphoreTake(data_ready_sem, portMAX_DELAY);
        process_data();  /* Doorbell rang — do the work */
    }
}

void app_main(void) {
    data_ready_sem = xSemaphoreCreateBinary();
    xTaskCreate(sensor_task, "sensor", 4096, NULL, 5, NULL);
    xTaskCreate(process_task, "process", 4096, NULL, 5, NULL);
}
```

### Mutex — Protecting Shared Resources

Use when multiple tasks need to access the SAME resource (UART, SPI bus, global data structure, I2C bus).

```c
/* PC Analogy:
   Mutex = a single key to a shared office bathroom
   Only one person can be inside at a time
   Others wait outside until the key is returned */

static SemaphoreHandle_t i2c_mutex;

void task_a(void *arg) {
    while (1) {
        xSemaphoreTake(i2c_mutex, portMAX_DELAY);  /* Take the key */
        /* Only this task uses I2C here */
        i2c_read_sensor();
        xSemaphoreGive(i2c_mutex);  /* Return the key */
        vTaskDelay(pdMS_TO_TICKS(1000));
    }
}

void task_b(void *arg) {
    while (1) {
        xSemaphoreTake(i2c_mutex, portMAX_DELAY);  /* Wait for key */
        /* Now safe to use I2C */
        i2c_write_display();
        xSemaphoreGive(i2c_mutex);  /* Return the key */
        vTaskDelay(pdMS_TO_TICKS(2000));
    }
}

void app_main(void) {
    i2c_mutex = xSemaphoreCreateMutex();
    xTaskCreate(task_a, "task_a", 4096, NULL, 5, NULL);
    xTaskCreate(task_b, "task_b", 4096, NULL, 5, NULL);
}
```

### Semaphore vs Mutex — When to Use Which

|Situation|Use|
|---|---|
|Task A signals Task B that event happened|Binary semaphore|
|ISR signals task that interrupt fired|Binary semaphore|
|Protecting a shared peripheral (I2C, SPI, UART)|Mutex|
|Protecting a shared data structure|Mutex|
|Counting available resources (e.g. buffer slots)|Counting semaphore|

### Golden Rules

```
Rule 1: Never call xSemaphoreTake inside an ISR
        Use xSemaphoreGiveFromISR instead

Rule 2: Always give back what you take
        Every Take must have a Give
        Forgetting to Give = deadlock

Rule 3: Keep mutex-protected sections short
        Long sections block other tasks unnecessarily

Rule 4: Never call vTaskDelay while holding a mutex
        Other tasks waiting for the mutex are starved
```

